There are two problems though. The first one is that if South gets in he may take too many \D tricks. But the bigger problem is that North cannot possibly have either of those two high cards. You and dummy together hold 28 HCP and South must surely hold the other 12 since he opened the bidding. Neither simple finesse will work so you must try what is called a Backward Finesse.

Hold up the \DA until the third round to confirm that North has only 2. He does. Then play four rounds of \Cs ending in your hand.

Now play the \HJ. If South doesn't cover, you will let it ride for your ninth trick. But South does cover so you must take dummy's \HA. Next play a small \H from dummy and finesse the \H9, hoping North has the \HT. This is the Backward Finesse.

